              		<table><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText"><h3>Problem Statement</h3></td></tr><tr><td class="statText">    </td><td class="statText"><p>A positive integer is called a palindrome if it reads the same forward and backward.  Integers containing leading zeros are not valid.  For example, 12321 is a palindrome, but 123210 is not.  You are given an int <b>K</b>.  Return the <b>K</b>-th palindrome, where the 0th palindrome is 1, the 1st palindrome is 2, etc.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText"> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText"><h3>Definition</h3></td></tr><tr><td class="statText">    </td><td class="statText"><table><tr><td class="statText">Class:</td><td class="statText">IntegerPalindrome</td></tr><tr><td class="statText">Method:</td><td class="statText">findByIndex</td></tr><tr><td class="statText">Parameters:</td><td class="statText">int</td></tr><tr><td class="statText">Returns:</td><td class="statText">long</td></tr><tr><td class="statText">Method signature:</td><td class="statText">long findByIndex(int K)</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText">(be sure your method is public)</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td class="statText">    </td></tr><tr><td class="statText"></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText"> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText"><h3>Constraints</h3></td></tr><tr><td align="center" valign="top" class="statText">-</td><td class="statText"><b>K</b> will be between 0 and 1000000000 (10<sup>9</sup>), inclusive</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText"> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="statText"><h3>Examples</h3></td></tr><tr><td align="center" nowrap class="statText">0)</td><td class="statText"></td></tr><tr><td class="statText">    </td><td class="statText"><table><tr><td class="statText"><table><tr><td class="statText"><pre>8</pre></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td class="statText"><pre>Returns: 9</pre></td></tr><tr><td class="statText"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td align="c